WEBVTT

00:00:01.520 --> 00:00:08.160
<v Speaker 1>Gracias por venir Gracias por venir in Spanish means thanks for coming

00:00:08.140 --> 00:00:10.060
<v Speaker 1>Gracias por venir.

00:00:10.060 --> 00:00:11.820
<v Speaker 2>Gracias por venir.

00:00:11.820 --> 00:00:14.940
<v Speaker 1>So there's two things that we can see in this sentence.

00:00:14.940 --> 00:00:20.300
<v Speaker 1>We can use this sentence as like a hook to remember two important things about Spanish.

00:00:20.020 --> 00:00:23.140
<v Speaker 1>The first thing is that we have two words for for.

00:00:23.140 --> 00:00:26.100
<v Speaker 1>We already saw another word for for.

00:00:26.100 --> 00:00:28.500
<v Speaker 1>For example, how are we saying for me

00:00:29.840 --> 00:00:30.800
<v Speaker 2>Para mi.

00:00:30.800 --> 00:00:31.760
<v Speaker 1>Para mi, good.

00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:34.640
<v Speaker 1>And for you speaking informally.

00:00:34.640 --> 00:00:35.440
<v Speaker 2>Para ti.

00:00:35.600 --> 00:00:36.480
<v Speaker 1>Para ti.

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:39.920
<v Speaker 1>So we had mi and ti coming with prepositions.

00:00:39.920 --> 00:00:41.920
<v Speaker 1>Para mi, para ti.

00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:52.520
<v Speaker 1>de mi from me de di from you but then for the other people we just say for he for example so how is for him or for he in Spanish

00:00:53.620 --> 00:00:54.580
<v Speaker 2>Para él.

00:00:54.580 --> 00:00:54.900
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:00:54.900 --> 00:00:57.060
<v Speaker 1>And for her.

00:00:57.060 --> 00:00:58.100
<v Speaker 2>Para ella.

00:00:58.100 --> 00:00:58.660
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:00:58.660 --> 00:01:03.060
<v Speaker 1>So this para is when something is for somebody.

00:01:02.760 --> 00:01:03.239
<v Speaker 1>No?

00:01:03.239 --> 00:01:10.920
<v Speaker 1>So for example, if we want to say this is for you, speaking informally, let's say it's a masculine object.

00:01:10.920 --> 00:01:13.000
<v Speaker 1>This this one is for you.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:14.759
<v Speaker 1>How would you say that?

00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:18.560
<v Speaker 1>What is tonight?

00:01:18.560 --> 00:01:19.760
<v Speaker 2>Ah, esta.

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:21.840
<v Speaker 1>Good, so that's your hook and you go from there.

00:01:21.840 --> 00:01:22.880
<v Speaker 1>Esta noche.

00:01:23.200 --> 00:01:26.000
<v Speaker 1>But I want a masculine thing.

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:27.360
<v Speaker 2>Esto?

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:30.479
<v Speaker 1>What you should do is look at somewhere that you've used it.

00:01:30.479 --> 00:01:32.560
<v Speaker 1>So you should look at this car.

00:01:32.560 --> 00:01:33.280
<v Speaker 2>Este.

00:01:33.280 --> 00:01:34.479
<v Speaker 1>And then you find it.

00:01:34.479 --> 00:01:37.440
<v Speaker 1>These are the processes that we're learning, and this is half of the method.

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:38.880
<v Speaker 1>You can take yourself

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:41.159
<v Speaker 1>through those processes when you need to find it.

00:01:41.159 --> 00:01:41.560
<v Speaker 2>Yeah.

00:01:41.960 --> 00:01:43.640
<v Speaker 1>And then it comes to your memory.

00:01:43.720 --> 00:01:44.840
<v Speaker 1>Then you know it after that.

00:01:44.840 --> 00:01:49.560
<v Speaker 1>But the first few times you need to have a look around, let's say, and see to find it.

00:01:49.560 --> 00:01:53.560
<v Speaker 1>So this or this one, masculine thing.

00:01:53.240 --> 00:01:54.840
<v Speaker 1>Este.

00:01:54.840 --> 00:01:59.960
<v Speaker 1>So this one is for you speaking informally.

00:02:00.119 --> 00:02:01.240
<v Speaker 2>Este S

00:02:01.820 --> 00:02:02.780
<v Speaker 2>Para ti.

00:02:02.780 --> 00:02:03.340
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:03.340 --> 00:02:05.980
<v Speaker 1>Este es para ti, if we mean a masculine thing.

00:02:05.980 --> 00:02:11.100
<v Speaker 1>What if you meant these are for you, uh masculine or mixed things

00:02:12.380 --> 00:02:14.700
<v Speaker 2>Estos son para ti.

00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:15.500
<v Speaker 1>Well done.

00:02:15.500 --> 00:02:17.820
<v Speaker 1>Estos son para ti.

00:02:17.820 --> 00:02:22.140
<v Speaker 1>So we saw that actually for this and this we have este and estos.

00:02:21.960 --> 00:02:26.680
<v Speaker 1>In este we have the e of el and in estos we have the os of los.

00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:28.440
<v Speaker 1>Estos son para ti.

00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:31.720
<v Speaker 1>So this is the four that we learned until now.

00:02:31.540 --> 00:02:32.260
<v Speaker 1>No?

00:02:32.260 --> 00:02:35.780
<v Speaker 1>Then we have por, which is much more flexible.

00:02:35.780 --> 00:02:38.340
<v Speaker 1>It has many more meanings.

00:02:38.340 --> 00:02:40.820
<v Speaker 1>Let's investigate some of them.

00:02:40.820 --> 00:02:41.620
<v Speaker 1>Poor.

00:02:41.620 --> 00:02:44.500
<v Speaker 1>You can use it like because of.

00:02:44.620 --> 00:02:48.940
<v Speaker 1>No, sometimes when we say for in English, we mean because of.

00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:53.980
<v Speaker 1>For example, if you say for this reason, what you mean is because of this reason.

00:02:53.980 --> 00:02:55.820
<v Speaker 1>So you don't mean para.

00:02:55.740 --> 00:02:57.100
<v Speaker 1>You mean por.

00:02:57.100 --> 00:03:00.940
<v Speaker 1>So por also means for in the sense of because of.

00:03:00.940 --> 00:03:05.180
<v Speaker 1>And actually in the words because and why, which were

00:03:06.440 --> 00:03:07.320
<v Speaker 2>Porque.

00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:08.040
<v Speaker 1>Porque.

00:03:08.280 --> 00:03:12.040
<v Speaker 1>Here in Y we see that it's because of.

00:03:12.040 --> 00:03:15.720
<v Speaker 1>Porque Y actually means because of what?

00:03:15.620 --> 00:03:16.980
<v Speaker 1>Because of what?

00:03:16.980 --> 00:03:25.540
<v Speaker 1>And then porque as because we said that we have the same word for wine because means because of that.

00:03:26.319 --> 00:03:30.319
<v Speaker 1>So in both cases you have por meaning because of.

00:03:30.319 --> 00:03:34.880
<v Speaker 1>So reason in Spanish is razón.

00:03:34.620 --> 00:03:48.860
<v Speaker 1>Rason or Razon in most of Spain Razon but in most of the Spanish speaking world rason rason is feminine, so how would you say this reason?

00:03:48.900 --> 00:03:50.100
<v Speaker 2>Esta razón.

00:03:50.340 --> 00:03:50.740
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:50.740 --> 00:03:55.060
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say because of this reason I don't want to go?

00:03:55.060 --> 00:03:58.260
<v Speaker 1>Because of this reason I don't want to go.

00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:07.200
<v Speaker 1>Let's contrast the two.

00:04:07.200 --> 00:04:08.320
<v Speaker 1>What was to buy?

00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:10.160
<v Speaker 1>Do you remember tobai?

00:04:13.300 --> 00:04:18.500
<v Speaker 1>Comprar good comprar you can say I'm buying it for you.

00:04:18.820 --> 00:04:19.620
<v Speaker 1>How would you say that?

00:04:19.620 --> 00:04:20.740
<v Speaker 1>Let's keep it informal.

00:04:20.740 --> 00:04:22.340
<v Speaker 1>I'm buying it for you

00:04:23.599 --> 00:04:25.120
<v Speaker 1>Lo compro para ti.

00:04:25.120 --> 00:04:25.440
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:27.039
<v Speaker 1>Lo compro para ti.

00:04:27.039 --> 00:04:30.080
<v Speaker 1>That means, you know, this thing I'm buying it for you.

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:33.919
<v Speaker 1>But maybe in some context you want to say I'm buying it because of you.

00:04:33.919 --> 00:04:35.680
<v Speaker 1>How would you say that?

00:04:36.340 --> 00:04:38.260
<v Speaker 2>Lo compro por ti.

00:04:38.260 --> 00:04:38.580
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:38.580 --> 00:04:40.020
<v Speaker 1>Lo compro por ti.

00:04:40.020 --> 00:04:46.340
<v Speaker 1>So it doesn't mean necessarily that this thing is for that person, just that you've bought it because of that person.

00:04:46.340 --> 00:04:46.740
<v Speaker 1>No?

00:04:46.980 --> 00:04:47.300
<v Speaker 1>So

00:04:47.660 --> 00:04:57.180
<v Speaker 1>Maybe you buy an ashtray in your house and your one friend that smokes comes and you say, Lo he comprado por ti, I have bought it because of you.

00:04:57.260 --> 00:05:03.420
<v Speaker 1>If you say lo he comprado para ti, for you, then he'll want to take that straight home.

00:05:03.420 --> 00:05:05.020
<v Speaker 1>Another use for por

00:05:05.840 --> 00:05:07.520
<v Speaker 1>is when we're talking about time.

00:05:07.520 --> 00:05:13.920
<v Speaker 1>When you're talking about periods of time, for two weeks, for two days, you will not say para, you will say por.

00:05:13.920 --> 00:05:16.400
<v Speaker 1>This is another place where you use por.

00:05:16.400 --> 00:05:18.800
<v Speaker 1>The word for day is dia, dia

00:05:19.720 --> 00:05:20.360
<v Speaker 2>Dia.

00:05:20.360 --> 00:05:21.160
<v Speaker 1>Dia.

00:05:21.160 --> 00:05:34.280
<v Speaker 1>It's actually related to an Indo-European root, which just means a very old root, meaning light and daiti in English comes from the same root.

00:05:34.380 --> 00:05:38.620
<v Speaker 1>Or the J of Jupiter is actually also from this root.

00:05:38.620 --> 00:05:42.060
<v Speaker 1>Jupiter means something like the father of the gods.

00:05:42.060 --> 00:05:48.620
<v Speaker 1>You have Peter like paternal there and Ju from this same root.

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:57.480
<v Speaker 1>As Dianneity, and of course you have Jupiter, which is the biggest planet, so the father of the gods Jupiter

00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:08.759
<v Speaker 1>Dia is a word that looks feminine and it's one of those few words that end in a that look feminine that are masculine.

00:06:08.759 --> 00:06:10.120
<v Speaker 1>So the day is

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:16.620
<v Speaker 1>El día andos

00:06:19.180 --> 00:06:22.780
<v Speaker 1>And every day is all the days.

00:06:22.780 --> 00:06:26.860
<v Speaker 1>Before we said todo el tiempo, to say all the time.

00:06:26.860 --> 00:06:29.740
<v Speaker 1>If you want to say every day, you say all the days.

00:06:29.740 --> 00:06:31.980
<v Speaker 1>How do you think that would sound?

00:06:32.860 --> 00:06:34.139
<v Speaker 1>Todos los días.

00:06:34.139 --> 00:06:34.620
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:34.620 --> 00:06:35.180
<v Speaker 1>Todos.

00:06:35.180 --> 00:06:35.979
<v Speaker 1>In plural.

00:06:35.979 --> 00:06:37.660
<v Speaker 1>Todos los días.

00:06:37.660 --> 00:06:38.300
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:38.300 --> 00:06:43.340
<v Speaker 1>If you wanted to say I'm staying for three days, three is tres.

00:06:44.420 --> 00:06:46.100
<v Speaker 1>I'm staying for three days.

00:06:46.100 --> 00:06:48.340
<v Speaker 1>I remain myself for three days.

00:06:48.340 --> 00:06:49.460
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say that?

00:06:49.460 --> 00:06:51.380
<v Speaker 1>I'm staying for three days.

00:06:52.760 --> 00:06:55.720
<v Speaker 2>Me quedo por tres días.

00:06:55.720 --> 00:06:56.600
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:06:56.600 --> 00:06:59.480
<v Speaker 1>Me quedo por tres días.

00:06:59.480 --> 00:07:01.480
<v Speaker 1>I'm staying for three days.

00:07:01.480 --> 00:07:05.640
<v Speaker 1>How would you say I will stay for three days?

00:07:05.420 --> 00:07:07.180
<v Speaker 1>I will stay for three days.

00:07:07.180 --> 00:07:09.340
<v Speaker 1>You don't really need you don't need the will here.

00:07:09.340 --> 00:07:14.060
<v Speaker 1>The fact that you say for three days is already some kind of uh future context

00:07:13.940 --> 00:07:15.860
<v Speaker 1>No, the days didn't happen yet.

00:07:15.860 --> 00:07:18.020
<v Speaker 1>But let's practice the future.

00:07:18.020 --> 00:07:21.780
<v Speaker 1>So I will stay for three days.

00:07:21.680 --> 00:07:23.600
<v Speaker 2>So it's giv.

00:07:23.600 --> 00:07:26.880
<v Speaker 1>In both futures we are adding on to the verb, huh?

00:07:27.120 --> 00:07:27.920
<v Speaker 1>Givare.

00:07:27.920 --> 00:07:29.920
<v Speaker 1>Yes, we are pushing it into the future.

00:07:29.920 --> 00:07:32.960
<v Speaker 1>So I will stay for three days.

00:07:33.660 --> 00:07:36.540
<v Speaker 2>Me quedaré por tres dias.

00:07:36.540 --> 00:07:36.940
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:07:36.940 --> 00:07:40.060
<v Speaker 1>Me quedaré por tres dias.

00:07:40.060 --> 00:07:44.620
<v Speaker 1>So this sounds a little bit more certain, you know, when you use the the future.

00:07:44.560 --> 00:07:51.680
<v Speaker 1>Me quedo por tres días, I'm staying for three days, me quedaré por tres días, I will stay for three days.

00:07:51.680 --> 00:07:54.240
<v Speaker 1>How would you say I would stay for three days?

00:07:54.240 --> 00:07:56.240
<v Speaker 1>I would stay for three days.

00:07:56.500 --> 00:08:01.860
<v Speaker 1>A nice hook to remember wood is a I would like or it would please me.

